content: Leonardo DiCaprio reveals the films he can't stop watching
reason: Joke A satirizes DiCaprio's obsession with Titanic by connecting it to his private island's value, while Joke B makes a general statement about his career.
joke_llama: "Leonardo DiCaprio's watchlist revealed he still obsessively watches Titanic – mainly so we're reminded that one day his private island will also go down with sinking values."
joke_qwen: Leonardo DiCaprio can't stop watching his own movies, proving he's better at starring in them than producing reality TV.

content: Hades II review - underworld sequel is an improvement in every witch way
reason: Both jokes satirize the review's claim of improvement by highlighting a humorous flaw in the sequel.
joke_llama: "Critics say Hades II improved everything about its underworld predecessor – except our chance of escaping it and living above ground again."
joke_qwen: In Hades II, every decision you make leads you back to the overworld—because let’s face it, even the Underworld needs its share of bail money.

content: Paranormal activity YouTuber arrested over video claiming new airport is haunted
reason: Both jokes satirize the headline, but Joke A is funnier due to its wordplay and unexpected twist.
joke_llama: "Some Paranormal Activity guy claimed our shiny new airport was haunted – now he's 'checking out' via handcuffs, probably booked solid with a free one-way flight."
joke_qwen: A paranormal activity YouTuber was arrested after claiming a new airport was haunted—police said they found no ghosts, but did confiscate all his jump scares and fake EVPs.

content: US players will ‘do the right thing’ over controversial Ryder Cup pay, insists Keegan Bradley
reason: Both jokes satirize the headline by poking fun at the potential for ethical dilemmas in professional golf.
joke_llama: Keegan Bradley's convinced US golfers 'll do the right thing with their Ryder Cup paychecks – mainly so they can afford therapy after playing under all that pressure... and also having their countrymen fund it.
joke_qwen: Keegan Bradley assures us all US players will “do the right thing” about the Ryder Cup pay dispute—because when faced with controversy, golfers always choose ethics... unless ethics involve more golf balls in the rough.

content: NFL kickoffs are no longer a dull formality. Previous strategies are now ‘obsolete’
reason: Both jokes satirize the change in NFL kickoff strategies, but Joke B's comparison to nuclear missiles is more creative and humorous.
joke_llama: "The NFL's getting rid of boring kickoff rituals – I guess 'dull' was an open-field tackle by last season's offense strategy."
joke_qwen: In the old days, kickoffs were like sending out an email—routine and safe. Now? They're like launching a nuclear missile. Guess all those fancy return specialists are now obsolete too—because now, everyone’s trying to start World War III on Sunday afternoons.

content: 5 writers make the 2025 CBC Nonfiction Prize shortlist
reason: Joke A satirizes the idea of writers needing caffeine to write, while Joke B makes a generic observation about the shortlist.
joke_llama: Five Canadian non-fiction writers made it onto this prestigious prize shortlist – I'm shocked no one's written about the real controversy: why the coffee shop across from them ran out of actual writer's block-ignoring caffeine.
joke_qwen: Five writers make the 2025 CBC Nonfiction Prize shortlist—and now everyone knows there were at least five good books this year.

content: Feeling overwhelmed What is ‘executive dysfunction’ and how do you overcome it?
reason: Both jokes satirize the headline by personifying 'executive dysfunction' as a CEO with relatable struggles.
joke_llama: Meet 'Executive Dysfunction' – where your brain's like a CEO with ADHD, except instead of delegating tasks, it delegates excuses to your therapist.
joke_qwen: Feeling overwhelmed? Executive dysfunction means your brain’s CEO is calling in sick, leaving your minions to sort through your inbox while you stare at the ceiling pondering why everything is still red.

content: Inside the courtroom for Australia's biggest trials
reason: Both jokes satirize the crowded and dramatic nature of Australian courtroom trials.
joke_llama: "Welcome to Australia's biggest trials – where you can watch justice unfold alongside 50 strangers and an aunt you hadn't noticed was invited."
joke_qwen: Inside the courtroom for Australia's biggest trials? Bring tissues—there’s enough drama here to make soap operas blush... unless you prefer your melodrama in 140 characters or less.

content: Markets Wrap European Stocks Fall as France Plunged Into Crisis
reason: Both jokes satirize the headline, but Joke A's pun on 'liberté' is more clever and relevant to the stock market context.
joke_llama: European stocks fell apart like French relationships – turns out 'liberté' includes liberty from our investments' value this quarter.
joke_qwen: European stocks fell, except for France, which plummeted into crisis... and then realized it was just another day at the office.

content: 30 sweaters we're shopping for fall: Cardigans, turtlenecks and more
reason: Both jokes satirize the headline's focus on numerous sweater types, but Joke B's comparison to a thermostat-disputing royal couple is funnier.
joke_llama: We've got so many sweater sales this fall – cardigans, turtlenecks, you name it – I'm starting to think the real question is why anyone needs an entire collection before November even arrives.
joke_qwen: In the land of fashion, where every sweater promises warmth but none guarantee actual heating bills, cardigans and turtlenecks reign supreme—like a king and queen who can’t agree on whether to turn up the thermostat or go commando.

content: Between Moon TidesHacking nature to save the saltmarsh sparrow
reason: Joke B directly relates to the headline by satirizing the idea of 'hacking' nature to save the sparrow.
joke_llama: Conservationists claim you can 'hack' nature by installing fake nests – essentially, it's like me trying to 'hackle' my dating life with an online profile claiming I'm outdoorsy when really I've never seen grass past my doorstep.
joke_qwen: Scientists are hacking moon tides to save the saltmarsh sparrow, proving even the lunar calendar needs an app to keep up.

content: US bans Iranian officials at UN summit from ‘shopping spree in New York’
reason: Joke A better satirizes the headline with its sarcastic take on 'diplomatic relations'.
joke_llama: "Breaking news: Iran's UN reps can't go shopping in NYC – talk about depriving a nation of its favorite pastime, now America really knows what it means by 'diplomatic relations'!"
joke_qwen: A US ban stops Iranian officials' shopping spree in New York, but they can still bring their own money—just no receipts.

content: Al Gore’s satellite and AI system is now tracking sources of deadly soot pollution
reason: Both jokes satirize the headline, but Joke A is funnier due to its clever wordplay and jab at Gore's Nobel Prize aspirations.
joke_llama: "Al Gore's got an app that tracks soot pollution – basically his carbon footprint tracker, but with fewer Nobel Prize chances."
joke_qwen: Al Gore’s satellite and AI system track deadly soot pollution—now we can finally know exactly where it comes from... and hope they’re not both still in development.

content: Drone sighting shuts major European airport as thousands stranded
reason: Both jokes satirize the headline, but Joke A is funnier due to its wordplay.
joke_llama: Some genius spotted a drone over Paris Charles de Gaulle Airport and suddenly everyone's flights got delayed – I guess you could say it was an 'in-flight' issue... but literally no one was flying.
joke_qwen: A drone sighting shut down a major European airport, leaving thousands stranded—and now everyone’s wondering why they didn’t just book a ferry instead.

content: Canoe believe this view? Hundreds of paddlers set to perform on Toronto's lakefront
reason: Joke A better satirizes the headline by playing on the word 'stroke' in the context of both paddling and musical performances.
joke_llama: "Hundreds of synchronized canoeists are about to paddle onto Toronto's lakefront – I guess it's'stroke' performances now instead of concert ones."
joke_qwen: Imagine hundreds of paddlers stretching out on Toronto’s lakefront—now imagine trying to navigate those canoes through the sea of elbows. Canoe believe it’ll fit?

content: UK is open to overseas talent unlike US, Reeves says
reason: Both jokes satirize the headline, but Joke A's comparison of visa queues to walls is more clever and humorous.
joke_llama: The UK claims it's welcoming to foreign talent - I guess when America says 'build a wall', they're like, "Oh no, we'll build a visa queue."
joke_qwen: UK opens its doors to foreign talent while America insists on green cards, proving the old saying: when Britain invites you in, they want you to stay forever—even if just for tea.
